'''T<U+1EA1> Phong T<U+1EA7>n''' (born 1968 at district V<U+0129>nh L<U+1EE3>i, in the province B<U+1EA1>c Li<U+00EA>u<ref name=CAND>{{cite web |url=http://antg.cand.com.vn/vi-VN/sukien/2010/7/72848.cand |title=T<U+1EA1> Phong T<U+1EA7>n - Ng<U+01B0><U+1EDD>i <U+0111><U+00E0>n b<U+00E0> v<U+00E0> trang blog <U+0111><U+1ED9>c h<U+1EA1>i|publisher=CAND |date=15/07/2010}}</ref><ref name=AFP>{{cite web |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h5wJ9WLSVrYUWx5XYm1nrOBAalnQ?docId=CNG.69ccddf7142dfbdb9467276fac249ecb.21 |title=Vietnam blogger's mother 'dies in self-immolation' |author=Cat Barton |date=30 July 2012 |publisher=Google News |agency=Agence France-Presse |archivedate=14 August 2012 |deadurl=no|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vTNm2JK |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref>) is a Vietnamese dissident blogger. A former policewoman and a member of the Communist Party of Vietnam, she was arrested in September 2011 on anti-state propaganda charges for her blog posts alleging government corruption.<ref name=G>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/jul/31/vietnamese-blogger-mother-fire-tan |title=Vietnamese blogger's mother sets herself on fire as daughter faces trial |date=31 July 2012 |work=The Guardian|deadurl=no |archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vQjCymf |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=BBC164>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-17727373 |title=Vietnamese bloggers deny charges, third in leniency bid |date=16 April 2012 |archivedate=14 August 2012|deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vPpreB5|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> On 30 July, Ta Phong Tan's mother Dang Thi Kim Lieng [[self-immolation|immolated herself]] in front of the government offices in [[Bac Lieu]] province in protest of the charges against her daughter.<ref name=BBC307>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-19053910 |title=Mother of Vietnamese blogger 'burns herself to death' |date=30 July 2012 |publisher=BBC News|deadurl=no |archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vQ5ejQh |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> On 4 October 2012, Ta Phong Tan was sentenced to ten years in prison. Her arrest was protested by groups including the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]], the [[US State Department]], [[Amnesty International]], and [[Human Rights Watch]].

== Blogging ==
When she began to blog, Ta Phong Tan worked as a policewoman.<ref name=BBC070313>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/vietnamese/vietnam/2013/03/130307_ta_phongtan_award.shtml |title=Ngo<U+1EA1>i tr<U+01B0><U+1EDF>ng M<U+1EF9> t<U+1EB7>ng gi<U+1EA3>i b<U+00E0> T<U+1EA1> Phong T<U+1EA7>n|publisher=BBC |date=3/7/2013}}</ref> In 2004, she became a freelance journalist.<ref name=VOA>{{cite web |url=http://www.voanews.com/content/mother_of_detained_vietnam_blogger_self-immolates/1449313.html |title=Mother of Detained Vietnamese Blogger Self-Immolates |author=Michael Lipin |date=30 July 2012 |publisher=Voice of America|deadurl=no |archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vSAnZ9y |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> Two years later, she started a blog titled ''Cong Ly va Su That'' ("Justice and Truth"), which became popular for its reports on police abuses.<ref name=G/><ref name=BBC307/><ref name=VOA /> Because of these reports and the criticism on the web about the policies of the Communist Party of Vietnam, she was expelled from the Party and lost her job in 2006.<ref name=CAND/><ref name=BBC070313/>

She was arrested in September 2011 along with fellow dissident bloggers [[Nguyen Van Hai]] and [[Phan Thanh Hai]], all of whom had posted through the "Free Vietnamese Journalists' Club". The three were charged with writing anti-state propaganda.<ref name=G/> The charges carried a maximum sentence of twenty years' imprisonment.<ref name=BBC164 /> The ''[[Economist]]'' described the arrests as "the latest in a series of attempts by Vietnam's communist rulers to rein in the country's blossoming internet population."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2012/08/internet-freedom-vietnam?fsrc=scn/tw/te/bl/anoddonlinerelationship |title=An odd online relationship |date=9 August 2012 |work=The Economist |archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vTenf8t |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref>

The UN [[Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights]] criticized the arrests, stating its concern for "what appears to be increasingly limited space for freedom of expression in Viet Nam".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=42620&Cr=Vietnam&Cr1= |title=UN concerned at shrinking space for freedom of expression in Viet Nam |date=3 August 2012 |publisher=United Nations |archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vU0wXM3 |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> In a July 2012 visit to Hanoi, US Secretary of State [[Hillary Clinton]] expressed concern for the detention of the three members of the Free Vietnamese Journalists' Club.<ref name=G/> [[Amnesty International]] described the three as [[prisoners of conscience]] and urged their release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.amnesty.org/en/news/viet-nam-halt-crackdown-freedom-expression-2012-08-07-0 |title=Viet Nam: Halt crackdown on freedom of expression  |date=7 August 2012 |publisher=Amnesty International |archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vUVK9pE |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> The [[International Federation for Human Rights]] and [[World Organisation Against Torture]] also released a joint statement calling on the Vietnamese government to release the three bloggers unconditionally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omct.org/human-rights-defenders/urgent-interventions/viet-nam/2012/08/d21886/ |title=Viet Nam: Pro-democracy bloggers face harsh penalties in upcoming trial |date=14 August 2012 |publisher=World Organization Against Torture |archivedate=14 August 2012|deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vUAdsul |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref>

== Mother's self-immolation ==
On the morning of 30 July 2012, Ta Phong Tan's 64-year-old mother, Dang Thi Kim Lieng, set herself on fire outside the Bac Lieu People's Committee in protest of her daughter's detention, one week before Tan's trial was set to begin.<ref name=AP>{{cite web |url=http://www.kansascity.com/2012/07/31/3735203/vietnam-bloggers-mom-self-immolates.html |title=Vietnam blogger's mom self-immolates before trial |agency=Associated Press |date=31 July 2012 |work=Kansas City Star |deadurl=no|archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vSPQlSE |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=G2 /> Lieng died of her burns en route to the hospital. The death was the first reported self-immolation in Vietnam since the 1970s.<ref name=G2 />

Vietnamese state media did not acknowledge the death for several days before stating that it would investigated.<ref name=G2>{{cite web |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2012/aug/05/vietnam-blog-shame |title=Vietnam's blog shame |author=Kamila Shamsie |date=5 August 2012 |work=The Guardian |archivedate=14 August 2012|deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vRp0DCm |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> An indefinite postponement was announced in Tan's trial.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/vietnam-probes-immolation-bloggers-mother-16918865#.UCsCTT1lS18 |title=Vietnam Probes Self-Immolation of Blogger's Mother |date=3 August 2012 |publisher=ABC News |deadurl=no|archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vTDpSzo |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref>

The US Embassy in Vietnam stated that it was "concerned and saddened" by the news, and reiterated its calls for the bloggers' release.<ref name=AP /> The US-based [[Committee to Protect Journalists]] called Lieng's death "a shocking reminder that Vietnam's campaign against bloggers and journalists exacts an unbearable emotional toll on the individuals involved."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpj.org/2012/07/imprisoned-bloggers-mother-self-immolates-in-vietn.php |title=Imprisoned blogger's mother self-immolates in Vietnam |date=30 July 2012 |publisher=Committee to Protect Journalists |archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vSh1tLa |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] called on the international community to address the underlying human rights situation, stating, "This is not just a tragedy for one family. This is a tragedy for the whole country."<ref name=AFP/>

A large number of mourners journeyed to Lieng's home to pay respects in the week following her death, though many were reportedly intercepted on the roads by state security forces. The government also placed Lieng's mourners under surveillance by plainclothes police officers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/vietnam/self-immolation-08022012184457.html |title=Authorities Watch Mourners |author=Khanh An |date=2 August 2012 |publisher=Radio Free Asia |archivedate=14 August 2012 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/69vT2PeOL |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref>

== Sentence ==
On 4 October 2012, Ta Phong Tan was sentenced to ten years in prison in a one-day hearing that ''The Economist'' compared to a [[Soviet Union]] [[show trial]].<ref name=E /> Prosecutors stated that the three had "distorted the truth about State and Party, created anxiety among citizens and supported schemes to overthrow the government", and the court found that they were "seriously affecting national security and the image of the country in the global arena."<ref name=E /> Phan Thanh Hai, who had pled guilty, was sentenced to four years' imprisonment, and Nguyen Van Hai to twelve years.<ref name=E>{{cite web |url=http://www.economist.com/blogs/banyan/2012/10/free-speech-vietnam |title=Bloggers flogged |author=L.H. |date=4 October 2012 |work=The Economist |archivedate=30 October 2012|deadurl=no |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Bow9bN7N |accessdate=30 October 2012}}</ref> The sentences were upheld by an appeals court on 28 December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-20856696 |title=Court appeal of dissident Vietnam bloggers is rejected |date=28 December 2012 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=2 January 2013 |archivedate=2 January 2013 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6DNwc92ai |deadurl=no}}</ref>

== Awards ==
In December 2012, Ta Phong Tan was one of 41 people to win a Hellman/Hammett award from Human Rights Watch, which recognizes writers suffering from political persecution.
<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-312585560.html |title=Vietnamese Bloggers Recognized for Commitment to Rights: 5 Win Prestigious Hellman/Hammett Awards|date=20 December 2012 |publisher=States News Service {{Subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}|accessdate=12 April 2013}}</ref> In 2013, she was named a winner of the [[International Women of Courage Award]] of the [[US State Department]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/vietnam/ta-phong-tan-03082013153228.html |title=Jailed Vietnamese Blogger Named 'Woman of Courage' |author=Rachel Vandenbrink |date=8 March 2013 |publisher=Radio Free Asia |accessdate=9 March 2013 |archivedate=9 March 2013 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Ezu3jAbf |deadurl=no}}</ref> In the ceremony on [[International Women's Day]], US Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] said of her, "For her dedication to continually demanding a better government for her people, for her willingness to take risks for her beliefs, and for her life experience and skills as a writer that serve as an inspiration to women in Vietnam, Ta Phong Tan is a 2013 woman of courage."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2013/03/205892.htm |title=Remarks at the International Women of Courage Awards |date=8 March 2013 |publisher=US Department of State |accessdate=9 March 2013 |archivedate=9 March 2013 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6EztyBe8X |deadurl=no}}</ref>

